Headlines.Author: Brendan Conway
Headlines.Headline: In Obama Budget, Boosts Seen For Some Equities

PARAGRAPH.#text: NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--Worries about the national debt aside, President Barack Obama's budget this week brings a few positives for stocks. Most notably, permanency could be coming on the subject of dividend and capital-gains taxes. In proposing to keep rates steady for joint tax-filers earning less than $250,000 and to raise them to 20% from 15% for the wealthy, the president promises to put an end to a debate that keeps investors in a state of annual suspense. Some analysts predict any tax hike's negatives will be small compared to the relief that comes when rates aren't put to debate every year.

    may not be what you think they are. "Bond-fund risk is just not well
    understood," says
, an economist with the

. While bond funds do invest in bonds, they don't behave like
    them. They cannot guarantee return of principal because they never actually mature,
    returns are tied as much to daily price movement as to the interest rate they pay, and
    income generated by the fund isn't fixed - it fluctuates with market rates.

    Corp.

dove 28 percent Friday after reporting better-than-expected earnings but
    forecasting falling profits in the second quarter. The telecommunications equipment maker
    earned 37 cents a share in the first quarter, surpassing the consensus estimate of 35
    cents. In the same period in 1996, Ciena earned 13 cents. Sales rose to $134.3 million
    from $53.9 million a year ago. Ciena said it may report a decline in second-quarter
    earnings due to reduced orders from WorldCom. The company also cited continued uncertainty
    about shipments to AT&T. Analysts were looking for second-quarter earnings of 37 cents
    a share. Ciena said WorldCom has reorganized its purchasing system, but will resume
    significant purchases of Ciena equipment in late 1998. Ciena plunged 16 1/8, closing at
    42.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Ciena flogged, sees lower Q2

Headlines.Headline: Taxing capital gains headaches

#text: Be ready for "several waves of panic," warns

,
    vice president at

, a record keeping service for more than 235
    mutual fund companies. Gore is referring to the filling out of your 1997 tax return and
    dealing with the headaches that mutual fund capital gains are likely to create. One
    sure cause for anxiety, reported the Wall Street Journal Friday, is the sudden realization
    that the loser fund in your portfolio may also be hit by a capital gains tax. According to
    fund trackers at Morningstar, Invesco
    Asian Growth

had a capital gain of nearly 21 percent even though it finished the year
    down 38.5 percent. Unlucky investors with a $10,000 stake in that fund would have suffered
    a loss of $3,850 but would be liable for taxes on a $1,300 distribution. Other taxing
    pitfalls brought out by the Journal included new forms required by the

for mutual fund filers (Schedule D), the probability that tax
    statements from fund groups (Form 1099-Div) will not correctly differentiate between long
    term and short term gains, and late tax statements (as late as April) to shareholders of
    closed-end funds and Real-Estate Investment Trusts.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Taxing capital gains headaches

Headlines.Author: Brenon Daly
Headlines.Headline: DOJ broadens Microsoft investigation

#text:
The Justice Department sent civil subpoenas to America
    Online

, MCI
    Communications

and other Internet service providers (ISPs) as part of its antitrust
    investigation of Microsoft

.
    The Justice Department's move appears to focus on whether the ISPs agreed to favor
    Microsoft's
    browser over the rival browser from Netscape
    Communications

. The government's current case against Microsoft alleges that the
    company is
    violating a 1995 consent decree by requiring computer makers to distribute its Web browser
    as a condition of licensing its basic Windows operating software. Shares in the world's
    largest software company rose 1/4 to 155 1/8. Microsoft's stock split 2 for 1 after the
    market's close on Friday. Share prices will reflect the split beginning on Monday.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: DOJ broadens Microsoft investigation
